tatus" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001005-20180328-161318"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="4"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="greg"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Regional Politics</CodeD><CodeI org="rbc" action="add"><CodeA name="rule" value="802906"/><CodeA name="db" value="prbc---00018596-20180328-144656"/><CodeA name="rule" value="849546"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001005-20180328-161318"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001005-20180328-161318"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="3"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipc">G/IGV N/CRM N/GEN N/PLT R/NME R/NY R/NYC R/US R/USE </DescField><DescField fid="ipd">WSJ WSJ.com WSJ.com Site Search WSJAsia WSJEurope WSJ Japanese Online WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com WSJSunday ANDREW CUOMO NY SEX HARASS POLICY SEXUAL HARRASSMENT SB123055822488121348798045841281012970067621 Cuomo, Andrew Flanagan, John Heastie, Carl SYND CODES_REVIEWED New York </DescField><DescField fid="ipcns">NYNY </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">US</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Cuomo Faces Pressure to Let Female Lawmaker Into Harassment Talks; Governor had vowed to include Senate's minority leader, Andrea Stewart-Cousins, but she says he hasn't followed through</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>ALBANY, N.Y.—As Gov. Andrew Cuomo and three male lawmakers meet privately to hash out a state sexual-harassment policy as part of the annual budget, they are facing calls to include the state's only female caucus leader in the talks.</Para><Para>Mr. Cuomo <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-york-female-legislator-will-join-all-male-group-developing-sex-harassment-policy-1518744022">vowed in February to include Senate Minority Leader Andrea Stewart-Cousins</ELink>, a Democrat, in the otherwise all-male group amid calls for her inclusion from women's rights groups. But with just a few days left before the budget deadline, Ms. Stewart-Cousins said Mr. Cuomo hasn't followed through on that pledge.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>"I'm not in the meetings, and I have not been included in other ways," she said in an interview Tuesday.</Para><Para>Among the ideas for new sexual-harassment policies are ending taxpayer settlements for sexual harassment within state government, refusing state contracts to companies with a history of sexual harassment, and setting uniform standards throughout state agencies.</Para><Para>Asked about Ms. Stewart-Cousins' exclusion, Mr. Cuomo on Wednesday told reporters that a "working group" of women in government was helping to negotiate the sexual-harassment policy and that her caucus had a representative to the group.</Para><Para>Mr. Cuomo's counsel, Alphonso David, said Tuesday that he disagrees with the idea that Ms. Stewart-Cousins has been excluded. Mr. David has met with two attorneys who represent her caucus in recent weeks to negotiate the budget, and Mr. Cuomo has spoken with her by phone, he said.</Para><Para>"That's not a negotiation, that's a briefing," Ms. Stewart-Cousins said, adding that Mr. Cuomo only spoke to her about "generalities."</Para><Para>Mr. David said Ms. Stewart-Cousins hasn't been included in the four-way talks among legislative leaders—known as "leaders' meetings" or "men in a room" in Albany parlance—because those have historically included only majority conference leaders.</Para><Para>"If a woman was representing a [legislative] majority, that would be great," he said.</Para><Para>Stewart-Cousins supporters say this year is different because sexual-harassment policy is expected to be part of the budget, and a woman's voice should be at the table for it.</Para><Para>Of the four men in the group negotiating the budget, Senate Majority Co-Leader Jeffrey Klein, a Bronx Democrat, is under state investigation over allegedly sexually harassing a former staff member. Mr. Klein has denied kissing Erica Vladimer, the former staffer, and said he welcomes the probe.</Para><Para>Meanwhile, Mr. Cuomo is <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/n-y-ignored-sex-harassment-claims-against-ex-cuomo-aide-says-state-workers-suit-1511127123">being sued for allegedly ignoring complaints</ELink> that his former aide sexually harassed Lisa Marie Cater, a former state employee. Mr. Cuomo's office has said it investigated Ms. Cater's claims but she was uncooperative.</Para><Para>The other two men at the budget meetings are Senate GOP Leader John Flanagan, of Long Island, and Democratic Assembly Speaker Carl Heastie, of the Bronx.</Para><Para>Ms. Vladimir and a group of other women who said they were sexually harassed in Albany by state officials wrote a letter to Mr. Cuomo earlier this month urging him to include Ms. Stewart-Cousins in the leaders' meetings.</Para><Para>"There are 10 million women in New York," they wrote. "They are not represented when there is not one woman in the room."</Para><Para>A spokesman for the Senate GOP said female members of its conference have been "very involved on this issue," pointing to legislation they put forward this year to end taxpayer settlements for sexual harassment. Mr. Heastie's budget positions are based partly on recommendations from a legislative work group of mostly women, a spokeswoman for the Assembly Democratic speaker said.</Para><Para>Mr. Klein "is in lockstep with Stewart-Cousins" on how to change the state's sexual-harassment laws, a Klein spokeswoman said, "and he looks forward to making it law."</Para><Para>The back and forth between Ms. Stewart-Cousins and Mr. Cuomo comes as he faces a primary challenge from actress Cynthia Nixon, who on Tuesday sided with Ms. Stewart-Cousins. "At a time when women across the country are demanding that their voices be heard, Gov. Cuomo is crafting sexual-harassment policy with someone accused of sexual misconduct and with zero women at the table," a Nixon campaign spokeswoman said.</Para><Para>A Cuomo spokeswoman pointed to several high-ranking female aides who attend the leaders' meetings.</Para><Para>The talks this year are complicated by the power dynamics of the New York state Senate. Republicans now hold power in a conference that includes eight Democrats who caucus with the GOP. But under pressure from liberal advocates, Mr. Cuomo earlier this year backed a deal in which Democrats could reclaim control of the Senate if they were to win a special election on April 24 that would also require the eight Democrats to caucus with their party.</Para><Para>Asked if she would include minority conference leaders in budget talks should she become a majority leader, Ms. Stewart-Cousins said that decision appears to rest with the governor. "It's not my room," she said.</Para><Para>Write to Mike Vilensky at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:mike.vilensky@dowjones.com">mike.vilensky@dowjones.com</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Mike Vilensky </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cuomo-faces-pressure-to-let-female-lawmaker-into-harassment-talks-1522242001" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

